Self Improvement  How I optimised my life to make my job redundant - Troy Hunt&rsquo;s point of view Write a brag document -  Get your work recognized: write a brag document You Are Your Own Best Hype Person Brag now, remember later: Document your accomplishments   Being visible - Why visibility matters Being Glue - If you stop doing those things, the team won&rsquo;t be as successful. But now someone&rsquo;s suggesting that you might be happier in a less technical role. If this describes you, congratulations: you&rsquo;re the glue. If it&rsquo;s not, have you thought about who is filling this role on your team? Three crucial skills that leaders must develop to become executives - These skills include taking (almost irrational) career risk, learning to scale by trusting your team, and developing advanced soft skills. Making the case to decision makers: the presentation format to follow - A tested template to follow when presenting to executive leadership teams. How to be a tech influencer | Will Larson -  Most successful people are not well-known online Being well-known online can be bad Most successful folks are prestigious in some way Content creation is an effective way to create prestige It&rsquo;s hard to measure influence Don&rsquo;t assume everyone&rsquo;s playing the same game   The impact of less scalable work | Will Larson - &ldquo;Less scalable&rdquo; work is more impactful than &ldquo;more scalable&rdquo; work if it reaches folks who are themselves in high impact roles Hard to work with | Will Larson - I&rsquo;ve seen a staggering number of folks fail in an organization primarily because they want to hold others to a higher standard than their organization’s management is willing to enforce A forty-year career | Will Larson  Pace  The biggest barrier to a forty year career is burnout, and preventing burnout is twofold First, work on work you find meaningful Second, manage your pace   People  Your current coworkers also have an outsized influence on your career long after you&rsquo;ve stopped working together It requires some deliberate focus to approach each new role with the intention of building the network of folks you know and work with well, but the compounding value of doing so is huge   Prestige  In retrospect, many folks' prestige seems inevitable, but is the result of deliberate, intentional action over an extended period With each bit of prestige you accumulate, gathering the next bit gets easier   Profit  As you get deeper into your career, you&rsquo;ll move into increasingly senior roles, and there are considerably fewer such roles available The process takes longer, and time depends upon money. Consequently, the best roles are only accessible if you’re already financially stable Financial security is a prerequisite to own your pace and learning   Learning  A forty year career has ample space and need for extended periods of both &ldquo;learning deep&rdquo; and &ldquo;learning broad&rdquo;     A career ending mistake - An insightful essay to help you assess where your career is going and where you want to go Work / Life Balance  Work and life distinction How to think about balance Balancing techniques Wake up and smell the roses Embrace the suck Anti-patterns Changes   Expiring vs. Long-Term Knowledge - How much of what you read today will you still care about a year from now?  Questions to ask
 &ldquo;How am I doing compared to your expectations?&rdquo; &ldquo;What do you see as my strengths &amp; weaknesses?&rdquo; &ldquo;What skills do I need to get to next level?&rdquo; &ldquo;Any tips on professional development?&rdquo;  Promotions  Does the title even matter? - Why titles do matter How to get promoted - Almost everyone who does great work toils in relative obscurity. Performance reviews are social fiction. How do people really advance through the corporate hierarchy?  Questions to ask
 &ldquo;Can we walk through the expectations for the next level to make sure I understand them?&rdquo; &ldquo;What&rsquo;s the most effective thing I can do to make myself a stronger candidate?&rdquo; &ldquo;What areas do you think I should focus on?&rdquo; &ldquo;What are the requirements needed to advance?&rdquo; &ldquo;What are the skills that I&rsquo;ll need to demonstrate?&rdquo; &ldquo;How can I best demonstrate them?&rdquo; &ldquo;If I don&rsquo;t get promoted this cycle, what are some of the likely causes?&rdquo; Examples  &ldquo;I&rsquo;m ready to move ahead in the organization&rdquo; or &ldquo;I will be ready soon&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;m enjoying what I do and I look forward to taking on more&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;d like to be a candidate for the manager position that&rsquo;s coming up&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve only been here for two years, but I&rsquo;ve learned a lot and I want to keep learning and growing&rdquo;
